I look gross, sweaty, slouchy, and tired. But this is the perfect picture to capture how my weekend went. @bearded_bowfisher took this on the last bird of the day. We were all ready to be done. We downsized my flock from 90 to under 70 and filled the freezers with so many homegrown free-range birds!!! Shoutout to @kyla.anne.k  for coming out and helping us on the assembly line! We’d have never finished them all without you. 
Some of the birds hatched from eggs here on the homestead in February, while others had called this place home for 8 long years. It was a bittersweet day because I love each and every one of my birds. But I can only keep the productive ones who have a purpose here. 
and with the price and quality of meat these days in grocery stores, I think I’ll be doing more and more of this. One long day saved us over $300 on meat costs to feed our family and friends.

Babies everywhere… hatching every day.

Westfälische Tötleger - commonly known as the Westphalian Deathlayer- a rare German landrace breed developed over a 400+ year period exclusively in the North-Rhine Westphalia region. First introduced in the US in 2019, this breed is being brought back from near extinction. They are supposed to be an extremely hardy production breed. 

Just wanted to show them off. I got my hands on 10 chicks this year and now I have a beautiful young flock. They are the most docile and well-behaved birds I’ve ever owned.

Some of y’all asked to see how my plucker drill attachment works. I had a couple culls to do this morning so I tried to record a short video on it.

A few tips - If i was doing a bunch, I’d have given my setup more effort. I would recommend either hanging the chicken from a gambrel , or holding the chicken and clamping the drill to the table (i did that when I butchered 20 something, but for just 2 I had my mom hold them. She was a good sport 😂). 
-the only downside can be the mess it makes. It flings feathers everywhere. we just rake them up afterwards.
-the plucker you use is less important than your scalding temperature. Scald them correctly and the feathers slide right off regardless of what plucker you use.

(I do not own the music in this video)

What does hunting mean to you?

Does it mean paying thousands to a guide who’s only in it for the money? Someone who will do whatever it takes to cut in front of other hunters ruining every cove they blow through on their way to bag a pre-scouted gator and be back at the ramp in 45 minutes?
Because to me, that’s not hunting. Unfortunately, a $4000 paycheck for 1 trophy gator and $1.5-3k for smaller ones means these guides have no limits to what they will do and how they will do it.
Their methods costed us alot of opportunities as they would repeatedly cut in front of us and leave a wake of destruction in their path, ensuring they spooked every gator but the one they were trying to beat us to.
I get that these are public waters, but how would you feel if you were hunting public deer land and another hunter rolled up in front of you hootin and hollering and shooting. Just seems a bit crooked to me.

We’ve only been gator hunting for 3 seasons. Completely self-taught. We didn’t get a single shot opportunity our first season, and it wasn’t until the last few hours of our second season that something clicked and we started understanding these animals and how to hunt them.
 This year we’ve been able to identify, pattern, and consistently produce shot opportunities on a variety of gators for the first time. Now, we just have to learn what equipment and setups work best for our situation so that we can connect and land them dependably. 
All in all, I’m proud of how far we’ve come. We hunted one of the largest, most well-known gators in that lake and almost got him. That is a very validating feeling after not being able to get anywhere close to him in past seasons. We produced better shooting and snagging opportunities on that gator than some hunters will ever have in their lifetime. 
 The knowledge, experience, and memories made over these past few years are absolutely priceless. Studying these animals and learning how to outsmart them takes years, especially in these small SC lakes where the are so highly pressured. 
Can’t wait to get back out there next week! Gator season is far from over.. 🐊

And to my dad @johnweleazer for all the behind-the-scenes tractor work, sowing food plots, putting up electric fences, keeping em fed and cams running while I’m away. He’s got the same passion for hunting and management that I do and he’s a huge reason I am the way I am.
And finally, thank you to my biggest supporter. Who lifts me up when I’m feeling low and would go to the ends of the earth to see me smile,  @bearded_bowfisher . You had JUST sent me a text “I want a picture of a big buck and gator head side by side! sending good vibes to you, I love you so much”.
I dialed your number seconds after I pulled the trigger and heard him crash in the distance. I know you could barely understand what I was saying 🤣 
I am blessed to have you all in my life and to experience this with each and every one of you. I love y’all! I have the best family ❤️

My doe from yesterday! 🦌🍂
I watched the herd for an hour or more before taking my shot. We’re picky when it comes to shooting doe, and I also wanted to make sure a buck wasn’t trailing them.
You never want to take a doe who has milk or young fawns. You also don’t want to inaccurately judge size and end up with something less than mature.

As dark was falling, I finally made my decision and dropped this perfect 120lb freezer queen 50ft from where she stood.
The rest of the herd just kept eating acorns like nothing happened. 
A thought occurred to me in that moment of just how greedy some people are. I could’ve easily doubled up if I wanted to. But the thought of taking 2 deer in 1 hunt doesn’t sit well with me. I’ve known hunters who don’t hesitate at that opportunity, but that’s just not who I am. 
Plus, screw cleaning and processing 2 deer at the same time. I ain’t about that life 😆
